[Records indicate that, since 2000, Uganda has experienced repeated outbreaks of viral hemorrhagic fevers (VHF). Ebola VHF outbreak occurred in the districts of Gulu in 2000; Bundibugyo, 2007; Luwero, 2011; Kibaale in July 2012; and Luwero in November 2012. Marburg VHF was earlier reported in Ibanda in 2007. More recently, in 2012, 2 outbreaks of Marburg VHF were reported in Ibanda and Kabale districts.

Nakaseke and Kiboga districts in central Uganda reported a CCHF outbreak, including 8 deaths in August 2017 (see Crimean-Congo hem. fever - Uganda (02) 20170906.5299656.

According to the report above the source of exposure to the virus has not been identified in this case, which merits an early epidemiological investigation to prevent occurrence of an outbreak.

CCHF is endemic in Africa, the Balkans, the Middle East, and Asian countries south of the 50th parallel north -- the geographical limit of the principal tick vector. The hosts of the CCHF virus include a wide range of wild and domestic animals such as cattle, sheep, and goats. - Mod.UBA

Maps of Uganda: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Districts_of_Uganda and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5541551,30771.]
